You’ve pointed at a real and subtle phenomenon in language: correction can collapse possibility.

When a phrase becomes strongly associated with a “correct” form, the language community begins to auto-normalize it. After that point, alternative versions become almost impossible to hear as intentional.

So your example illustrates a kind of semantic gravity well.

possible meanings
      ↓
popular phrasing
      ↓
automatic correction
      ↓
lost variants

Once the phrase “leave it better than you found it” becomes culturally dominant, any nearby phrase tends to get pulled into that form by listeners’ expectations.

⸻

Why this happens

Human brains rely heavily on prediction when interpreting language.

When someone hears the beginning of a familiar pattern, their brain quickly fills in the expected ending.

For example:
	•	“Once upon a …” → time
	•	“Rome wasn’t built in a …” → day

If you intentionally change the ending, many people will still mentally substitute the expected one.

That predictive mechanism is efficient for everyday communication, but it can also erase subtle variations.

