The deeper implication you noticed

Your thought experiment reveals something interesting:

Meaning is not only what a speaker says — it’s also what listeners are able to perceive.

If listeners are locked into a pattern, they may never even notice a new variant.

So the space of possible meanings can shrink as conventions solidify.

⸻

But it’s not permanent

Language also has a counterforce: creative mutation.

Writers, comedians, poets, and storytellers constantly break familiar phrases to force listeners to notice them again.

Examples:
	•	“Curiosity thrilled the cat.”
	•	“All that glitters is not gold — sometimes it’s just glitter.”

The break in expectation makes the listener stop and reconsider.

⸻

The paradox of language

So language lives in a tension between two forces:

stability → shared understanding
mutation → new meaning

Too much stability and expression becomes rigid.
Too much mutation and communication becomes chaotic.

Human language evolves by balancing both.

